AGP, Megaworld, San Miguel, Semirara: Philippine Stocks Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-06-22T00:50:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-22/agp-megaworld-san-miguel-semirara-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 1.4 percent to
4,211.81.  AGP Industrial Corp. (AGP)  : The company’s shares will
resume trading today, ending a suspension that started March
2002, the Philippine Stock Exchange said in a June 14 advisory.
The company’s Class A and B shares will be combined into a
single type of stock that will have an indicative price of 3.76
pesos, the exchange also said.  Separately, the company said yesterday its board approved
the sale of 136.7 million shares at 1 peso each and the creation
of units for its expansion into real estate, mining and
agriculture.  First Philippine Holdings Corp. (FPH)  : The company
bought back 350,000 shares in the open market at 58.10 pesos
each, an exchange filing showed. The stock increased 0.5 percent
to 58.20 pesos.  Megaworld Corp. (MEG)  : The Philippine property builder
expects its net income to reach 6 billion pesos ($138 million)
this year, a stock exchange filing showed. The company had
reported profit of 5.03 billion pesos for 2010, data compiled by
Bloomberg show. The stock advanced 5.3 percent to 2 pesos.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  : Chairman Eduardo Cojuangco
legally acquired his 20 percent stake in the country’s largest
listed company by sales, the Philippine Supreme Court said
yesterday, rejecting the government’s appeal of an April ruling.
The stock gained 0.2 percent to 114 pesos.  Semirara Mining Corp. (SCC)  : The largest Philippine coal
producer’s board approved a plan to expand its power generation
capacity by 600 megawatts, a stock exchange filing showed. The
stock declined 3.9 percent to 208.20 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
